<TEXT>
world war ii hasnt quite ended for thousands of 
koreans who were brought by the japanese to work the coal mines of 
the pacific island of sakhalin more than 40 years ago 
refused exit by their new soviet overlords after the war the 
koreans have been forced to live in exile 
but their homecoming may finally be near with warming relations 
between the soviet union and capitalist south korea 
in the last month the soviets have begun talks with south korea 
through the red cross and other channels to solve the longfestering 
problem 
for many it could be too late of the 43000 koreans in sakhalin 
at the end of the war only 4000 to 5000 are thought to be alive 
om cholyoung is one of them 
conscripted by japan in 1943 to work as a coal miner while 
japans own workers were fighting the war om and his wife were 
taken to the japanesecontrolled southern half of sakhalin 
when the war ended om put his wife and infant son on a ship to 
korea thinking he soon would follow 
but in august 1945 the soviets extended their control to all of 
the north pacific island and om could not leave 
although korea also had been wrested from japanese colonial 
control it had been divided between the communist north and the 
south 
the soviets terminated contact between sakhalin and the south in 
effect extending the exile of om and others like him with families 
in the south 
exiles with families in north korea were apparently allowed to 
return but neither the soviet union nor north korea has confirmed 
it 
during his exile om later married another korean woman in 
sakhalin and had two children 
nevertheless he persisted in his goal of returning to his first 
wife and child in june he received permission to resettle in korea 
returning to korea was the only thing i asked from life om 
said in a recent interview in tokyo being in the soviet union was 
really hard its not that i didnt like it there but my wife and 
child were in korea 
now 74yearold om is back in south korea living with both his 
families in the southern port of pusan 
efforts to repatriate the koreans have long been thwarted by 
japanese indifference and tension between the soviet union and 
rigidly anticommunist south korea 
but the recent warming of relations between seoul and moscow 
reflecting eastwest detente and soviet recognition of south koreas 
growing economic power has given hope to sakhalin exiles 
before 1986 only a handful were allowed to meet with their 
families each year the number has increased dramatically 
this year 500 to 600 may ultimately be reunited with loved ones 
says kenichi takagi a tokyo lawyer and leader of a volunteer group 
that has sponsored most of the visits 
the reunions which previously were held in japan can now take 
place in korea moreover more than 10 koreans including om have 
received permission to move back to their homeland permanently 
under a sovietsouth korean agreement reached in the talks a 
chartered south korean plane may be allowed to take several hundred 
koreans from sakhalin before the end of the year sources from south 
koreas governing party said recently 
japan has also begun to take more interest in the fate of the 
exiles 
two years ago 170 members of the japanese parliament formed a 
nonpartisan group to promote a quick resolution of the issue at 
the groups urging the government this year set aside 405000 
toward repatriation efforts 
japanese leaders also have raised the issue in talks with the 
soviets 
takagi maintains japan should do more 
japan must take care of all the costs for the families to 
reunite it also must pay compensation for the 45 years that these 
people lost he said 
postwar germans have paid reparations to the jews and to 
israel they have conquered their past but japans debt to the 
korean people still remains repaying it is the responsibility of 
the japanese people 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

