<TEXT>
five japanese were arrested for trying to sell 
nearly nine pounds of refined uranium to the us embassy for 83 
million police said tuesday 
in concentrated form the radioactive chemical element can be 
used for nuclear power generation and nuclear bombs however 
nuclear experts said the substance offered by the suspects was 
nearly in its natural state and would require more processing for 
almost any use 
city police said the four men and a woman were arrested friday 
after offering to sell the uranium to the embassy in tokyo at about 
2000 times its market value 
police said they were tipped off about the case by the us 
embassy and secretly took pictures of the suspects in cooperation 
with the embassy before making the arrests 
police said they seized photographs from the suspects showing 
about 40 metal capsules that appeared to contain uranium they said 
the suspects offered to sell a total of 88 pounds of the substance 
authorities said tuesday the five were arrested for illegal 
possession of nuclear substances but had not been formally charged 
police said the suspects brought a capsule with 35 ounces of 
uranium to the embassy in early august and offered the rest for sale 
later 
police said they sent the substance in the capsule to the science 
and technology agency which found it was refined natural uranium of 
707 percent purity 
the analysis showed only 071 percent was uranium235 the kind 
used for power generation and bombs experts say nuclear power 
generation requires more than 3 percent uranium235 and an atomic 
bomb needs more than 90 percent of that same type 
nuclear experts including prof kyoji naito of nagoya 
univerisity said the uranium was almost in its natural state and 
thus had little use without further processing 
they said it could be harmful if the human body were exposed to 
it for an extended time 
the american embassy said laboratory analysis showed the 
substance had posed no danger to embassy personnel or the public 
naito and the police said the price the suspects demanded shows 
they did not know the uraniums value the same type is being sold 
at about 275 per ounce making the price the group demanded more 
than 2000 times greater than its market value 
takaharu ushikoshi head of the police departments public 
