<TEXT>
all 26790 new york city police officers will be 
subject to random drug testing the police commissioner announced 
tuesday 
the goal of random testing is to have a drug free 
environment commissioner benjamin ward said in a statement i 
believe that this expanded drug testing program will further promote 
that environment and provide a deterrent to the use of illegal 
drugs 
the new policy excludes civilian employees of the police 
department the department now requires random drug tests only of 
the 2000 officers in the narcotics division applicants for the 
detective division and the organized crime control bureau are also 
tested but not at random 
other officers can be tested based on administrative or medical 
cause 
under the new program all officers social security numbers will 
be entered into a computer which will select some at random for 
each test the officers chosen will have 24 hours notice of the test 
ward who was in washington was not available to comment on the 
policy change 
phil caruso head of the patrolmens benevolent association 
which represents police officers was also not immediately available 
for comment spokesman joe mancini said 
during 1988 3946 police officers were tested with 37 officers 
testing positive this year through july 2220 police officers 
were tested with 23 testing positive 
random drug tests are also required of candidates for police 
officer as well as police recruits at the police academy and at the 
completion of their probationary period 
it is expected that additional staffing will be necessary to 
administer the program and the lab costs of the drug testing are 
estimated at 31000 per year 
