<TEXT>
sir ronald syme an oxford historian who shook the 
dust from the study of ancient rome with his theories about the 
intrigues of its nobles has died at age 86 the university said 
tuesday 
syme died monday at an oxford hospital he entered last week said 
dr martin francis secretary of the governing body of oxfords 
wolfson college where syme had lived since 1975 the hospital did 
not give the cause of death 
he was probably the most eminent classicist of this century 
francis told the associated press 
his grasp of the language and concepts used in roman society 
combined with his sense of style has made him the foremost scholar 
of roman historiography kirsti simonsuuri senior research fellow 
at the university of helsinki wrote in a 1983 anthology of modern 
thinkers 
instead of focusing on the ideals and constitutional structure of 
the roman emperors as his predecessors had syme disclosed the lust 
for power and money that motivated their careers comparing them to 
european dictators in the 1930s 
he introduced the theories in his first and most famous book 
the roman revolution published sept 7 1939 
we were about to have a party to celebrate the 50th anniversary 
of the publication next thursday said francis who described syme 
as an upright courageous totally dedicated man 
syme was knighted in 1959 in 1976 he was awarded the order of 
merit britains most desired civil distinction which is limited to 
24 intellectuals and scientists 
born march 11 1903 in new zealand syme studied classics at 
oxford in the 1920s 
he worked for the british government during world war ii in 
embassies in yugoslavia and turkey then taught classical philology 
at the university of istanbul syme pioneered a method of historical 
research that involved studying the backgrounds of groups of 
influential people 
as part of his work syme held that the roman republic was 
transformed into an empire partly because of struggles between 
political factions surrounding the emperor augustus who died in the 
year 14 
although he retired in 1970 after 21 years as oxfords camden 
professor of ancient history syme continued to work until his 
death francis said 
his last book the augustan aristocracy was published in 
1986 of his later works a twovolume study of the emperor tacitus 
published in 1958 was generally seen as his masterpiece 
syme a bachelor was not known to have any immediate survivors 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

