<TEXT>
the following outlines components of president 
bushs national drug strategy at a glance the highlights of the 
strategy include 
350 million for states and local governments for criminal 
justice law enforcement and prison systems 
12 billion for construction of federal prisons 
requiring federally acceptable drug prevention programs and 
policies as a condition to receive federal funds for schools and 
colleges 
withholding federal criminal justice funds from states that do 
not have drug testing for prisoners parolees and people arrested 
and consider test results when determining sentencing bail and 
parole 
261 million to help the andean countries of peru bolivia and 
colombia fight drug lords 
more money for domestic eradication efforts 
tougher regulations for federal housing projects to expedite 
evictions of drug dealers and expand drug prevention programs for 
resident associations 
urges greater use of employee drug testing in state and local 
government and the private sector 
encourages stiffer penalties for drug users 
more federal money for community drug prevention efforts 
increased money for treatment programs to expand the number of 
people who can be treated the range of treatment programs and 
emphasize treatment for pregnant women who use drugs 
making receipt of federal treatment funds contingent on state 
and local compliance with federal standards for effective drug 
treatment programs 
expanded research and information coordination to evaluate and 
develop more effective treatments 
greater border interdiction emphasis on drugdetection dogs 
document fraud container inspection and other methods 
more emphasis on air interdiction and catching drug couriers 
and money launderers 
