an outbreak of cholera in chinas far western 
province of xinjiang has killed at least six people and 796 others 
have been stricken the official china daily newspaper reported 
wednesday 
it said the disease hit 17 southern counties in the remote 
mountainous province it blamed contaminated water and said a 
prolonged drought had aggravated the problem 
the local public health department said about 22 million rural 
xinjiang residents drink unclean water 
the public health ministry said china registered 89 deaths from 
cholera in 1988 most are believed to have occurred in xinjiang 
the china daily also reported an outbreak of polio in coastal 
jiangsu province with 440 cases reported between february and 
august it said 29 jiangsu children had died 
in all of china last year 584 cases of polio were reported the 
paper said 
ten years ago china had as many as 10000 polio victims a year 
authorities have said china hopes to eliminate polio by 1995 
however an immunization program has covered only about 60 percent 
of the nations children the health ministry said last year 
