<TEXT>
satire george s kaufman once warned is what closes on 
saturday night that didnt stop him from collaborating with moss 
hart on once in a lifetime the biting spoof of early hollywood 
the new hollywood with its buzzphrases lets take a meeting 
and do lunch and numbing vapidity and undercurrent of deceit 
could certainly provide ample material for a biting satire the 
big picture isnt it christopher guest and his collaborators are 
not kaufman and hart and their film proves annoyingly flat like a 
series of shaggydog stories without punchlines 
more was expected of guest who contributed some of the funniest 
sequences to saturday night live as writer and actor he also 
cowrote and appeared in rob reiners clever sendup of the rock 
world this is spinal tap 
guest who makes his feature debut as a director with the big 
picture cowrote the story with michael varhol who also 
produced they wrote the screenplay along with michael mckean they 
obviously took delight in conveying inside jokes trouble is 
many of them are too inside for the layman 
the big picture opens promisingly enough with an awards 
program at the national film institute student films most of them 
grossly pretentious are screened the winner is nick chapman kevin 
bacon an eager young filmmaker with high principles and a 
supportive girlfriend emily longstreth 
nicks award draws him into the hollywood vortex he is wooed by 
a variety of smarmy agents and signs with an orientallooking loony 
martin short who receives no billing 
a bigtalking studio chief jt walsh hires nick to direct his 
original script with dizzying speed nick betrays his principles 
dilutes his script betrays his best friend mckean and abandons 
his girlfriend for a starlet 
then one morning nick picks up the trade papers and finds the 
studio boss has been fired nicks project is dropped and he 
becomes unemployable after hitting bottom he directs a music video 
that makes him hot again he is able to film his original script 
hire his best friend and reconcile with his girl 
if guest intended a hollywood morality tale it doesnt work the 
characters are standard cliches and its hard to believe that 
nicks dopey screenplay would get a second look at any studio kevin 
bacon does his best to breathe life into the weakwilled nick but 
the character is hard to like or admire brief roles are played by 
eddie albert june lockhart john cleese and roddy mcdowall 
the columbia release is rated pg13 mostly for language running 
time 100 minutes 
