<TEXT>
 
cousins paramount home video vhs beta rated pg13 
 
cousins carries no suggested retail price because it is 
intended for the rental market good idea because its hardly worth 
the celluloid on which its filmed 
cousins is joel schumachers graceless treatment of 
jeancharles tacchellas charming 1976 comedy cousin cousine 
schumacher makes the mistake of trying to closely follow the 
original both open with a rousing family wedding scene in which the 
husband and wife of different couples meet run off for a little 
sexual fling and leave their respective mates waiting at the 
catering hall for their returns the cuckholded spouses start up a 
harmless flirtation and friendship and eventually have an affair of 
their own 
but where the original danced lightly with the passions and 
eccentricities of french culture the new version applies the thin 
moralistic veneer of an american tv sitcom with idiot level dialogue 
and conviction simply put the french have a different way of 
viewing adultery 
ted danson as compelling in this role as a bottle of warm flat 
champagne plays larry kozinski who is married to tish played with 
airhead finesse by sean young isabella rossellini perhaps cast in 
this movie to give it some sort of continental class and a little 
sunshine is maria hardy an understanding wife and mother married 
to a brutish bore named tom william petersen who sells suburus but 
who likes to say he sells bmws 
the truly comic moments which were many in cousin cousine 
are diluted in cousins by weighty and blunt situations when tom 
realizes maria and larry are also having an affair he confronts 
larry in typical hollywood macho style with if you go near my 
wife again ill kill you petersen is more fred flintstone than 
valentino 
what saves cousins from utter and total oblivion is the 
wonderful patter between larrys father lloyd bridges and larrys 
son mitch keith coogan grandpa and grandson have a bucolic 
moment over some girlie magazines and the scene in which mitch 
helps grandpa vince prepare for a date with marias mother norma 
aleandro is worth the rental 
a totally unnecessary addition to cousins is the subplot 
involving the boygirl problems tom and marias daughter experiences 
in preschool who cares 
perhaps hollywood will one day realize that some things get lost 
in translation one would think the lesson would have been learned 
in 1983 when jim mcbride remade jeanluc godards classic 1960 film 
breathless into a pathethic and misguided movie it starred 
richard gere who was embarrassing as he attempted to take on the 
role jeanpaul belmondo had created in the original 
something gets lost in the translation as hollywood puts its neon 
wand to french confections if it aint broke dont fix it 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
tap rcacolumbia pictures home video vhsbeta 8995 
rated 
 
movie audiences have yearned for those splashy joyous romantic 
musicals of the 1930s 40s and 50s when boy met girl boy lost 
girl boy got girl back and everybody lived happily everafter 
dancing all the way to the altar 
nick castle whose father choreographed many of those wonderful 
fred astaireginger rogers vehicles attempts to bring back those 
golden dance movies with tap a love letter to hoofers great and 
small 
starring gregory hines and some of the greatest tap kings living 
tap features excellent dancing and a splendid exuberance 
unfortunately the movie holds back the dance sequences never seem 
to totally reach their potential and on the small screen they may 
be lost altogether 
one production number in which hines takes a club full of tap 
fans out to times square to feel and hear the beat and rhythms of 
the city such as cars going over metal plates in the road or 
construction crews thumping the pavement and marks out a dance the 
number starts out well luring the viewer to the rhythms and moves 
then it fizzles 
another disappointment is the wistful rooftop soft shoe 
performed by hines and the lovely suzzanne douglas to cheek to 
cheek its a romantic fred and ginger takeoff that never really 
gets off how sad 
the biggest problem with tap is castles script and story 
line max hines is a genius dancer who unfortunately finds 
secondstory work more to his liking than hoofing after a stint in 
jail he returns to new york where he hooks up with the hoods again 
at the same time his mentor little mo sammy davis jr encourages 
him to resume his dancing and even tries to turn him on to a new tap 
innovation amplified shoes 
the plot though gets in the way of the dancing its not 
compelling poignant or interesting enough the tap dancing 
however is 
hines perhaps the greatest contemporary tap stylist around these 
days is marvelous his supporting cast includes savion glover a 
14yearold hoofer who one day will make the same claim there are 
also sandman sims bunny briggs harold nicholas jimmy slyde and 
steve condos some of the dancers who helped define and perfect the 
art and craft of tap in the 20th century 
forget the story view tap as a tribute to the great ones and 
to appreciate what tap dancing was all about before broadway and 
hollywood took away its snap and crackle 
</TEXT>
