<TEXT>
a rose by any other name might smell as sweet but 
relying on common names of plants can be a recipe for disaster or 
disappointment as gardeners moving to different climates after 
retirement discover quickly 
botanical names are the answer dont recoil in horror 
camellia bougainvillea aloe agave eucalyptus gardenia 
hibiscus philodendron verbena youre doing fine 
the toughest part is the first step deciding to insist on such 
identification before spending money time and effort on seeds or 
plants but it definitely ensures getting what you really want and 
being able to locate and follow the best directions for taking care 
of it 
for example in the eastern united states a muchrecommended 
shrub is the mock orange it is deciduous has white fragrant 
flowers in late spring mediumgreen foliage and needs minimal care 
it was a major asset everywhere in my former neighborhoods of 
suburban new york city philadelphia and washington 
botanically it is the philadelphus a member of the 
saxifragaceae family 
but ask for mock orange in southern california and youll 
likely get pittosporum tobira an evergreen member of the 
pittosporaceae family with entirely different needs than 
philadelphus about the only similarity is that the flowers smell 
like blossoms on orange trees 
after discovering this following a transfer to los angeles years 
ago i began an informal check on how many mock oranges were 
being sold in this country my counting stopped after 28 botanically 
different ones 
pittosporum tobira is a rugged magnificent performer outdoors in 
wide areas of the west and does great as a house plant in 
frostprone regions like the midwest and east its great for 
southern california but in arizona my retirement home it sunburns 
badly if grown under afternoon sun 
as another example at least a halfdozen different but 
oftenused shrubs are sold in phoenix as birds of paradise 
the most familiar in spectacular bloom in august is the 
mediumsized one caesalpina pulcherrima with orangeredandyellow 
flower clusters but even there the common name blurs it is called 
variously the mexican bird of paradise or red bird of 
paradise two yellowflowering cousins also are often called 
mexican bird of paradise 
the various birds of paradise sold here fall into two quite 
different families strelitzia and caesalpinia both are wonderful 
in supplying a tropical effect but once established the 
caesalpinias need little if any supplemental water take all the 
heat sun and cold of our desert and grow quickly the strelitzias 
like ample water and part shade can be killed by temperatures in 
the low 20s and grow slowly 
many nurseries in recent years have added the botanical name to 
the common on their labels its becoming common in most catalogs a 
fast way to learn is to use a reference that insists on the 
botanical names while also giving common names 
the botanical name of all roses incidentally begin with rosa 
by definition this is the genus plants consisting of one or more 
species from the same family and sharing many characteristics 
</TEXT>
