<TEXT>
this is one of a series of periodic reports 
looking ahead to western europe in 1992 when the 12 nations of the 
european economic community remove their trade barriers and 
interlock their policies and goals 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
once upon a time in america was one 
of the first movies a new european network showed when it went on 
the air this year 
in fact american shows are increasingly what the 320 million 
viewers in the 12 nations of the european economic community see 
almost every time they turn on their television sets 
be it the original batman series the odd couple star 
trek or dallas us programs pervade the airwaves and 
european politicians and artists are rallying against them 
after years of waffling the eec member nations will try to 
decide in october whether to stem the flood of us programming 
through quotas 
the united states is crying foul complaining about protectionism 
and fearing a loss of millions of dollars in trade 
but defenders of quotas here say european culture is at stake 
calling for protection as the eec prepares turn the community into a 
single trading bloc by the end of 1992 
writing to key members of the eecaffiliated european parliament 
recently carla hills the special us trade representative said 
quotas would be blatantly discriminatory patently unjustifiable 
and would almost certainly have a disastrous effect on the us 
industrys substantial european earnings 
experts said more homegrown productions may not improve the 
overall quality of european television and doubted whether europe 
can produce enough to replace us shows kept out by quotas 
this decade many european nations deregulated their television 
industries more than doubling air time which could be filled only 
with more us programs 
as early as 1982 culture minister jack lang of france called for 
a real crusade against lets call things by their name this 
financial and intellectual imperialism that no longer grabs 
territory or rarely but grabs consciousness ways of thinking 
ways of living 
he said he counted more than 200 hours of american shows in one 
week on the six french channels 
last year on belgiums rtltvi a commercial network 65 percent 
of the movies 83 percent of the series and 70 percent of the 
cartoons were americanmade according to parliamentary records 
quotas would hit the us television industry hard as it is 
increasingly using international sales to offset huge production 
costs 
george gerbner of the annenberg school of communications in 
philadelphia said in an interview that us producers had only 
three major buyers in the united states meaning the three big 
networks 
and they put the price so low that the domestic market only 
takes care of the cost for a profit they are forced onto the world 
market so there is a strong drive to get into as many markets as 
possible 
a decade ago the western european market for us television 
consisted of only a handful of state networks but more stations 
have since gone on the air and the competition for top shows has 
driven prices up 
lorimar telepictures corp which produces dallas has been 
seeing its international revenues rise by about 25 percent annually 
the series which sold for 12000 an episode in 1986 yielded four 
times as much in 1988 
today walt disney studios gets more than half its overseas 
television revenue from eec countries the communitys business for 
us producers swelled to more than 650 million last year from 100 
million in 1980 
the european public continues to gobble up american tv with great 
cheer despite pleas that they should not yield to cultural 
imperialism 
but american programs gave been on european tv screens for a long 
time chiefly because there was little else to chose from 
as long ago as the 1950s there was a void in tv schedules and 
only the us producers could work on such a massive scale said 
professor cees hamelink of the international association of mass 
communication research in the hague netherlands 
the process was selffulfilling larry gross also of the 
annenberg school said us television forces audiences to expect a 
level of production that europeans cant match 
to meet them you have to join them he said in an interview 
western europes new commercial networks do just that it is 
cheaper to show reruns of taxi alf benson and 
hogans heroes than to make their own programs or buy more 
expensive european series in any case major european series are 
not likely to be available in sufficient quantities for some time 
</TEXT>
