<TEXT>
discussing possible eec quotas jack valenti president of the 
motion picture association of america raised the question at a 
congressional hearing in washington earlier this year whether 
european producers can ever satisfy european viewers demands after 
so much american television 
yet the eec is moving ahead with plans to protect european 
television 
if not said jacques delors president of the eec commission 
all televisions will be made in japan and all programs will be 
american 
as early as 1984 the eec suggested a localcontent quota of 60 
percent this year this was watered down to a majority of european 
programs where practicable 
but the european parliament wanted precise figures and that has 
led to a stalemate the eec nations will reopen the debate in 
october 
meanwhile us television remains a political issue for the left 
and more recently the extreme right 
franz schoenhuber leader of the west german republicans rang 
the theme during election campaigns this year assailing dallas 
and other us shows on west german television 
we dont want the american way of life he said 
the french film director claude autantlara reflecting the views 
of many of his european colleagues talked about the terrifying 
threat to european culture from across the atlantic 
comparing the best in europes cultural heritage with american 
mass consumerism claude brule president of frances union of 
playwrights and composers begged europeans not to turn the 
grandchildren of moliere into those of cocacola 
the americans are seen as crude and rude and it is a continuing 
process said gross of the annenberg school 
it is a defensible argument to impose quotas on other cultures 
but the context and the reason have to be different than to think 
domestic is good and foreign is bad 
the culture split can even get blurred 
once upon a time in america which the belgian commercial 
station vtm showed on its opening weekend last winter is a us 
movie featuring lots of blood and gore however it was directed by 
sergio leone an italian 
not all us television gets a bad rap in europe nor does made 
in europe guarantee unrivaled quality 
on the day that the british and the continental europeans can 
make programs as good as hill street blues they may be in a 
position to talk about holding back american cultural imperialism 
wrote tv critic christopher dunkley in britains financial times 
early this year 
europeans have produced such successful programs as the british 
series jewel in the crown and brideshead revisited and the 
quality west german production berlin alexanderplatz 
but they are not the norm 
italys 250 or so mostly local stations lure viewers with endless 
jewelry sales game shows beauty contests and entertainment 
programs where culture is as sparse as clothing 
some experts see no european television style merely a spinoff 
of the us style they point to chateauvallon a french series 
titled after a fictive town or west germanys das erbe des 
guldenburgs the guldenburg inheritance which match the family 
feuds and romantic escapades of dallas 
they doubt whether quotas can change this since local programs 
would have to be mass produced to meet the new demand 
