<TEXT>
like modernday conquistadors foreign airlines 
are descending on the new world to buy up pieces of us carriers 
major us airlines have become hot properties stalked by 
bigtime investors unions and rival carriers foreign airlines are 
keen to get in on the action and the americans are eager to get the 
infusions of capital from abroad 
more importantly though the foreigners are taking equity stakes 
in order to help them gain access to the booming us air travel 
market which can augment their passenger traffic 
foreign airlines arent allowed under us law to own domestic 
airlines or carry passengers within the united states so many are 
linking up with american partners in special marketing agreements 
as big stockholders the foreigners can exert even more influence on 
the strategies of us carriers 
theyre using it to get a toehold in the us market said 
andrew geller an airline analyst at provident national bank in 
philadelphia 
british airways scandinavian airlines system klm royal dutch 
airlines swissair japan air lines and australias ansett transport 
industries ltd all have snapped up or are seeking equity stakes 
in us carriers 
the attraction is especially strong for european airlines which 
have been seeking ways of positioning themselves to exploit the era 
of common market deregulation that is set to begin in 1992 
sas the first foreign carrier to buy a stake in a us major 
signed a 50 million cooperation agreement with texas air corp last 
october and holds 99 percent of the houstonbased company sas 
recently has been in talks to buy a stake in struggling continental 
airlines one of texas airs main subsidiaries 
we had a very limited number of us gateways said nils flo 
an sas spokesman in new york explaining why the airline entered the 
agreement that gave it a feeder network in the united states 
