<DOCNO> AP890905-0244 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the commerce department ordered shrimp 
fishermen tuesday to install trap door devices in their nets to 
protect endangered sea turtles 
the decision came after months of controversy during which gulf 
coast shrimpers argued the requirement would threaten their 
livlihood 
shrimpers immediately denounced the government order and 
suggested some fishermen may not comply with the regulation despite 
a maximum 20000 fine per violation 
its going to drive a lot of people out of business 
maintained jimmy russell president of the 200boat brownsvilleport 
isabel shrimp producers association on the texas coast i wouldnt 
be surprised if they have a lot of people tell them theyre not 
going to do it 
the government directive came under a court order requiring the 
commerce department take action to protect the turtles thousands of 
which drown yearly when caught in the nets of shrimp fishermen 
primarily in the gulf of mexico 
the question of how to protect the turtles prompted lawsuits by a 
half dozen environmental groups seeking to protect the turtles and 
charges from shrimp fishermen groups that the use of the trap door 
devices will cause them to lose a significant part of their daily 
catch 
last july commerce secretary robert mosbacher suspended 
enforcement of a regulation requiring the devices after angry gulf 
coast shrimpers blockaded shipping channels along the texas coast 
and threatened violence against law officers and the coast guard if 
the requirement were enforced 
among the species to be protected by the socalled turtle 
excluder devices or teds are the kemps ridley leatherneck 
and hawksbill all of which are listed as endangered species and 
the loggerhead and green se turtles which are listed as being 
threatened 
in making the announcement john a knauss undersecretary of 
commerce said that under the federal endangered species act the 
only way to ensure protection of these vanishing species is through 
the use of teds 
there is no other choice knauss said in a statement 
the decision takes effect friday 
commerce spokesman brian gorman said violators could be fined as 
much as 20000 per violation although penalties likely will be in 
the 8000 range in most cases fishermen will have a grace period 
until oct 15 where all or some of the fine would be suspended if 
the violator installed the required net equipment 
knauss said attempts to protect the turtles by limiting the 
length of time that shrimpers nets are in the water an approach 
that has been tried in recent months was insufficient to protect 
the turtles 
the decision immediately was hailed by environmental group which 
had filed suit seeking the government to require that the trap door 
devices be used by gulf coast shrimpers many shrimpers off the 
south atlantic coast already use the devices 
the decision is certainly what we had hoped for said michael 
weber vice president of the center for marine conservation he 
added however that he expects possible legal attemps by shrimpers 
to get the decision reversed or pressure in congress to have the 
regulation changed 
basically were pleased but were sorry it took so long and we 
had to jump through so many legal hoops said charles miller a 
spokesman for the national wildlife federation at this point the 
turtles are going to have fighting chance 
the controversy over the use of the socalled teds has dominated 
this years gulf coast shrimping season 
last may the commerce department directed that the trapdoor 
devices be installed by shrimp fishermen in the gulf coast where an 
estimated 11000 sea turtles are reportedly drown annually when 
caught in the nets 
but the shrimpers loudly protested use of the teds an 
ovalshaped metal grate about four feet in diameter that is place 
inside the funnellike shrimp nets to allow large animals such as 
turtles to be diverted and escape through a special trap door 
the shrimpers argued that the devices also cause them to lose 
large amounts of shrimp as much as 40 percent of the catch 
according to some fishermen environmentalists have argued that such 
assertions are wrong and that at worst only about 2 percent of the 
shrimp catch is affected and possibly less if the teds are used 
properly 
because of economic concerns mosbacher ordered a twomonth delay 
in enforcing the federal requirement for the devices in july after 
sometimes violent protests erupted among some gulf coast shrimp 
fishermen over the use of teds mosbacher gave the shrimpers a 
choice of using the devices or limiting their thrawl times 
the federal courts however ordered a final rule to be issued by 
sept 8 prompting the commerce department decision tuesday to 
return to requiring the use of the trap door devices 
environmentalists warn that several of the sea turtle species 
especially the kemps ridley may be doomed to extinction in the 
coming decades if they are not protected from shrimpers nets the 
number of female kemps ridley sea turtles nesting each year has 
declined from some 42000 in the 1940s to no more than 700 today 
according to james ross an expert on sea turtles 
ross said that from 600 to 1600 kemps ridely turtles are killed 
each year often after the young turtles get in the way of the 
shrimping nets the decline of the species is estimated at about 3 
percent a year he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

