<TEXT>
the world bank owned by 151 countries is 
planning grants from a new 100 million package to help some of the 
worlds poorest countries pay off loans to commercial banks a 
spokesman for the world bank said tuesday 
it is expected that the governments will be able to buy back some 
of these commercial bank loans for a fraction of their original 
value 
world bank spokesman william brannigan said that the amount owed 
by any one country to any one bank would be small and that the 
banks would be glad to get the loans off their books 
possible candidates would be bangladesh and nepal in asia and 
countries in southern africa where average incomes are one dollar a 
year or less 
it is expected that a country would only be eligible if it is up 
to date on repayments of loans to the world bank itself and has set 
up a new economic program satisfactory to it or its sister 
organization the international monetary fund 
big debtors like brazil argentina and mexico would not qualify 
brannigan said the plan has been approved by the world banks 
board of executive directors 22 representatives chosen by the 151 
governments but he said approval is still needed from the board of 
governors which is composed of treasury secretary nochlas f brady 
who controls the largest single block of shares in the world bank 
and ministers of finance of the other member governments 
the board of governors will hold its annual meeting in washington 
at the end of this month 
brannigan said its approval is needed because the world bank 
wants to take the 100 million from 1 billion earned annually by 
its international bank for reconstruction and development and use 
the money for grants by its international development association 
the ibrd makes a profit by borrowing money at low rates on the 
market and lending it to third world governments at higher rates 
but for longer periods than those offered by commercial banks and to 
many countries they refuse to lend to 
ida makes loans to the poorest countries for as long as 50 years 
at less than 1 percent interest but normally does not make outright 
grants it gets most of its money from direct contributions by the 
united states and 32 other donor countries 
brannigan pointed out that money owed by the poorest countries 
was lent largely by governments and intergovernment bodies like the 
world bank it is estimated that the total they owe commercial banks 
is about 2 billion 
juergen warnke west germanys minister for cooperation told 
reporters last week that his country alone had cancelled more than 
44 billion in loans over the past 10 years 
president bush announced in july that the united states will also 
be canceling some debts estimated at 1 billion to the poorest 
countries 
</TEXT>
